prompt: ["Write a story about a heavily pregnant cavewoman"]
response_a:
["In the depths of a dark, damp cave nestled amongst the rocky cliffs, a heavily pregnant cavewoman named Ugta paced back and forth. Her belly was large and round, nearly as big as her own small frame. Her husband, Grom, sat by her side, handing her sips of water from a nearby stream.

Ugta had been in labor for what felt like an eternity. Her contractions were long and painful, and she had been in this state for what felt like days. Grom had been patiently waiting beside her, never leaving her side. He knew that this was a time of great danger for both his wife and their unborn child.

The cave was quiet, save for the sound of Ugta's grunts and moans as she pushed with all her might. The walls of the cave seemed to close in around them, suffocating them both. Grom's heart pounded in his chest as he tried to remain calm and collected.

Suddenly, there was a loud, bloodcurdling scream that echoed through the cave. Ugta's body jerked and contorted in pain, and then, with a final push, a small, wriggling baby emerged from her womb. Grom reached out to take the child, his heart filled with love and joy.

Ugta collapsed on the ground, exhausted and battered. Grom wrapped the baby in a soft fur blanket and held her close, feeling her warm, tiny body against his chest. He knew that their family was complete, and that they would face whatever challenges lay ahead together.

As they sat in the dim light of the cave, Ugta and Grom watched as their baby slept soundly in Grom's arms. They knew that this was a time of great danger, but they also knew that they had each other, and that was all that mattered.

The couple lay down to rest, their bodies and spirits exhausted, but their hearts filled with love and hope for the future. They knew that they would face whatever challenges lay ahead, together as a family, in the depths of the dark, damp cave nestled amongst the rocky cliffs."]
response_b:
["Ugga was a sturdy cavewoman, used to the rough and tumble life of the prehistoric world. But nothing could have prepared her for the weight of the massive boulder that had settled in her belly. For months, she had been carrying the child, and the strain was starting to show. Her once-slender frame was now rounded and swollen, her joints aching with every step.

Despite the discomfort, Ugga was determined to carry her child to term. She had always been a strong and capable hunter, and she wasn't about to let a little thing like pregnancy slow her down. But as the days passed, it became harder and harder to ignore the constant pain and fatigue.

One day, as she was out gathering berries with her tribe, Ugga's waters broke. She knew that she had to get back to the cave as soon as possible, but she also knew that the journey would be long and arduous. She gritted her teeth and began to make her way back, her companions rallying around her to offer support.

As they approached the cave, Ugga could feel the baby moving inside of her, kicking and squirming in anticipation of its new world. She gasped in pain as another contraction hit, her body trembling with the effort. But she refused to give up, determined to bring her child into the world no matter what.

Finally, after what felt like an eternity, Ugga reached the cave. She collapsed onto the cold stone floor, her companions rushing to her side to help. With their assistance, she pushed and pushed, her body straining against the weight of the baby.

And then, suddenly, it was over. Ugga had given birth to a beautiful, squalling baby boy, his tiny fists waving in the air as he took his first gasping breaths. She held him close, tears of joy streaming down her face as she gazed into his bright, curious eyes.

Despite the challenges of pregnancy, Ugga knew that it had all been worth it. She had brought a new life into the world, and she was ready to do whatever it took to keep him safe and healthy. As she cradled her baby in her arms"]

When updateTableLayout(2,3) is executed for example, the content of cell C2 (and its colspan/rowspan values) will be moved to cell A1, C3 to A2, D2 to B1, etc
The content of cell A1 will disappear in this case, because it falls out of the visibility range.
When updateTableLayout(2,3) is executed again, A1 should appear again.
The content of the cells in the rows and columns that appear now at the right and the bottom (because they weren't visible before) should now all contain the text "xx".
The content of all the cells of the table are also stored in a global javascript dict, named cachedCells.
The key is the Excel formatted name, the value is an object. This object has a property named data.
This data property contains the value of the cell.
The object also has a property named merge, which has 2 properties: col and row.
These 2 properties contain the colspan and rowspan of the cell.
E.g. cachedCells["A1"] = { "data": "blabla", "merge": { "row": 2, "col": 2 } }
If a cell is a partner of a merging area (e.g. cell A1 has a colspan of 3, cells A2 and A3 do not have a TD element and are seen as a merging area partner), they will still have a cachedCells element, but their data property will be empty and the row and col properties will be 0.
cachedCells should never be updated.

I created a test plan which contains all possible movements:

1) updateTableLayout(2,2) unmerged
 A1 B1 C1 D1
 A2 B2 C2 D2
 A3 B3 C3 D3
 A4 B4 C4 D4

becomes

B2 C2 D2 xx
B3 C3 D3 xx
B4 C4 D4 xx
xx xx xx xx

updateTableLayout(1,1) returns back to

A1 B1 C1 D1
A2 B2 C2 D2
A3 B3 C3 D3
A4 B4 C4 D4

2) updateTableLayout(2,2) merged column (B2 has colspan of 2)
 A1 B1 C1 D1
 A2       D2
 A3 B3 C3 D3
 A4 B4 C4 D4

becomes

      D2 xx
B3 C3 D3 xx
B4 C4 D4 xx
xx xx xx xx

updateTableLayout(1,1) returns back to

A1 B1 C1 D1
A2       D2
A3 B3 C3 D3
A4 B4 C4 D4


3) updateTableLayout(2,2) merged row (B2 has rowspan of 2)
A1 B1 C1 D1
A2    C2 D2
A3    C3 D3
A4 B4 C4 D4

becomes

   C2 D2 xx
   C3 D3 xx
B4 C4 D4 xx
xx xx xx xx

updateTableLayout(1,1) returns back to

A1 B1 C1 D1
A2    C2 D2
A3    C3 D3
A4 B4 C4 D4

4) updateTableLayout(2,2) merged row + col (B2 has rowspan=2 and colspan=2)
A1 B1 C1 D1
A2       D2
A3       D3
A4 B4 C4 D4

becomes

      D2 xx
      D3 xx
B4 C4"]
